Class MissingKeyException

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Throwable
      • java.lang.Exception
        • java.lang.RuntimeException
          • java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
            • com.radiusnetworks.util.MissingKeyException
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public final class MissingKeyException
extends java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
    A MissingKeyException may be thrown when a method is invoked with a map argument which does not contain an expected or required key.

    This is meant to express the absence of a mapping for a specified key. If instead the mapping is present but the value is null, and a null value it not permitted, use MissingValueException instead.

    Since:
    0.1.0
    See Also:
    IllegalArgumentException, Map.containsKey(Object), MissingValueException, Serialized Form

    • Constructor Detail

      • MissingKeyException

        public MissingKeyException(java.lang.String missingKey)
        Constructs a new MissingKeyException with the specified missing key.

        The detail message will be set to "Missing key: missingKey". The cause is not initialized and may subsequently be initialized by a call to Throwable.initCause(Throwable).

        Parameters:
        missingKey - The key missing from the map which caused this exception. The key is saved for later retrieval by the MissingKeyException.getKey() method. May be null as some maps allow null keys.

      • MissingKeyException

        public MissingKeyException(java.lang.String missingKey,
                           java.lang.Throwable cause)
        Constructs a new MissingValueException with the specified missing key and cause.

        The detail message will be set to "Missing key: missingKey". Note that the detail message associated with cause is not automatically incorporated in this missing key exception's detail message.

        Parameters:
        missingKey - The key missing from the map which caused this exception. The key is saved for later retrieval by the MissingKeyException.getKey() method. May be null as some maps allow null keys.
        cause - The cause of this exception. This is saved for later retrieval by the Throwable.getCause() method. May be null which indicates that the cause is nonexistent or unknown.

      • MissingKeyException

        public MissingKeyException(java.lang.String detailMessage,
                           java.lang.String missingKey)
        Constructs a new MissingValueException with the specified detail message and missing key.

        Note that missingKey is not automatically incorporated into the detail message. The cause is not initialized and may subsequently be initialized by a call to Throwable.initCause(Throwable).

        Parameters:
        detailMessage - The detail message for this exception. This is saved for later retrieval by the Throwable.getMessage() method.
        missingKey - The key missing from the map which caused this exception. The key is saved for later retrieval by the MissingKeyException.getKey() method. May be null as some maps allow null keys.

      • MissingKeyException

        public MissingKeyException(java.lang.String detailMessage,
                           java.lang.String missingKey,
                           java.lang.Throwable cause)
        Constructs a new MissingValueException with the specified detail message, missing key, and cause.

        Note that missingKey and the detail message associated with cause are not automatically incorporated in this missing key exception's detail message.

        Parameters:
        detailMessage - The detail message for this exception. This is saved for later retrieval by the Throwable.getMessage() method.
        missingKey - The key missing from the map which caused this exception. The key is saved for later retrieval by the MissingKeyException.getKey() method. May be null as some maps allow null keys.
        cause - The cause of this exception. This is saved for later retrieval by the Throwable.getCause() method. May be null which indicates that the cause is nonexistent or unknown.
